nt political issues, rather than politicians’ personal characteristics. Accordingly, the ads enrich the democratic process, providing voters with relevant and substantial information before they head to the polls. An important and timely contribution to American political discourse, In Defense of Negativity concludes that if we want campaigns to grapple with relevant issues and address real problems, negative ads just might be the solution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aadvertising, ads, negative, president, elections, electorate, campaigning, strategy, bias, slander, lies, deception, politics, political, america, american, united states, usa, pundit, journalist, journalism, voter, votes, voting, scholarly, academic, history, historical, qualifications, candidates, benefit, myth, 1960s, 1970s, 1980s, 1990s, 2000s, 20th century, bush, gore, clinton, obama, democracy.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226285009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226285009/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles